{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508010","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508010"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:44+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:00:44+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2699"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2699"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.05,0.2,0.4,0.29]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2699","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2699"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2699"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50113"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"181"},{"type":"tags","id":"1110"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3324"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3330"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8685"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8795"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17569"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the Gastroenterology clinic for follow up. She has alcohol-related cirrhosis diagnosed 10 years ago. She ceased drinking alcohol two years ago but her liver disease and its complications persist. She reports new abdominal fullness over the past few weeks. She denies any effect on her breathing or appetite. She has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has more than 10 spider angiomas across her chest and arms. Her liver is not palpable. Her abdomen is distended but not tense, with shifting dullness present consistent with mild-moderate ascites.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS) procedure","Low protein diet","Large volume paracentesis","1.5L fluid restriction","No-added salt diet"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with mild-moderate ascites as a complication of cirrhosis. The most appropriate initial management is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eno-added salt diet\u003C/strong\u003E. This dietary modification helps prevent fluid retention by reducing the osmotic drive for ascites formation. Patients should be educated on avoiding adding salt during cooking or at the table avoiding high-sodium pre-prepared meals. Significant salt restriction is not recommended in cirrhosis, as it is not effective in controlling ascites and may even lead to complications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnlike in heart failure, \u003Cstrong\u003Efluid restriction\u003C/strong\u003E is not needed or recommended in cirrhotic ascites unless hyponatraemia is also present. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransjugular intrahepatic portosystemic shunt (TIPS)\u003C/strong\u003E procedure is reserved for refractory ascites that has failed medical management. It carries risks including hepatic encephalopathy and should not be considered as initial management.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELarge volume paracentesis\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated for tense or symptomatic ascites causing respiratory compromise or significant discomfort. This patient\u0027s ascites is mild-moderate and should first be managed conservatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow protein diet\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect and potentially harmful. Patients with cirrhosis have higher protein requirements and are recommended a high protein diet to prevent muscle wasting (sarcopenia) and maintain adequate nutrition. Adequate protein intake improves survival and reduces complications in cirrhosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initiating dietary changes, if ascites persist or worsen, the next step would be to add diuretic therapy, typically starting with spironolactone. Regular monitoring of weight, electrolytes and renal function is essential. A diagnostic paracentesis should additionally be performed for new-onset ascites.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A no-added salt diet is recommended as part of initial management of cirrhosis-related ascites","Fluid restriction is not routinely needed unless hyponatraemia is present"],"references":["Aithal GP, Palaniyappan N, China L, et alGuidelines on the management of ascites in cirrhosisGut 2021;70:9-29. Available at: https://gut.bmj.com/content/70/1/9","Baki J, Brown P, Tapper EB. Do nutritional interventions improve the outcomes of patients with cirrhosis and ascites: A systematic review of Randomized Trials. Current Hepatology Reports. 2020;19(2):71\u20137."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50113"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2699"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50113"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T13:47:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T13:49:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2699"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64679"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"h